# Q13. Explain the different types of pins available on the Arduino UNO.

The Arduino UNO contains different types of pins used for power supply, input/output operations, analog sensing, and communication.

| Pin Type | Function |
|----------|----------|
| Digital Pins (0–13) | Used for digital input and output. Can read HIGH/LOW signals and control LEDs, relays, and other digital devices. |
| PWM Pins (3, 5, 6, 9, 10, 11) | Generate Pulse Width Modulation (PWM) signals for controlling LED brightness and motor speed. |
| Analog Input Pins (A0–A5) | Read analog voltages (0–5 V) from sensors using the built-in ADC. |
| Power Pins | Include 5V, 3.3V, GND, Vin, and Reset pins to power the Arduino and connected components. |
| Communication Pins | Pins 0 (RX) and 1 (TX) are used for Serial communication. A4 (SDA) and A5 (SCL) are used for I2C communication, while pins 10–13 are used for SPI communication. |

These pins allow the Arduino UNO to interface with a wide range of sensors, actuators, displays, and communication modules.
